ğŸ“Œ What is Linear Search?

Linear Search is a basic search technique where we check each element one by one until we find the target.





ğŸ”¹ Example:

 Imagine searching for a friendâ€™s name in a long list of contacts. You start from the first name and go one by one until you find the correct one.





ğŸ› ï¸ Linear Search in JavaScript

function LinearSearch(arr, target) {

    for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {

        if (arr[i] === target) {

            return i;  // Return the index if the target is found

        }

    }

    return -1;  // Return -1 if the target is not found

}

console.log(LinearSearch([10, 20, 30, 40], 40)); // Output: 3







ğŸ§ How Does This Work? (Step-by-Step)

For arr = [10, 20, 30, 40] and target = 40, the function:

 1ï¸âƒ£ Checks arr[0] â†’ 10 (Not a match)

 2ï¸âƒ£ Checks arr[1] â†’ 20 (Not a match)

 3ï¸âƒ£ Checks arr[2] â†’ 30 (Not a match)

 4ï¸âƒ£ Checks arr[3] â†’ 40 (Match found! Returns index 3) âœ…









â³ Understanding Time Complexity

Best Case (O(1)) â†’ If the target is found at the first position.

Worst Case (O(n)) â†’ If the target is at the last position or not in the array.

Average Case (O(n)) â†’ On average, we check half of the elements before finding the target.

ğŸ’¡ Linear Search is simple but inefficient for large datasets.

ğŸ’¡ Key Takeaways

âœ” Works on both sorted & unsorted arrays.

âœ” Easy to implement but slow for large datasets.

âœ” For large datasets, use more efficient search algorithms like Binary Search.





